Your issue comes from **mixing up concepts** of `pytest` (e.g. injection of fixtures like `variables`) with concepts of `unittest.TestCase`. While pytest supports running tests based on `unittest`, I&#39;m afraid that injection of plugins&#39; fixtures into test methods is [not supported](https://docs.pytest.org/en/latest/unittest.html#pytest-features-in-unittest-testcase-subclasses).

There is a workaround though that takes advantage of fixtures being injected into other fixtures and [making custom fixtures available](https://docs.pytest.org/en/latest/unittest.html#mixing-pytest-fixtures-into-unittest-testcase-subclasses-using-marks) in `unittest.TestCase` with `@pytest.mark.usefixtures` decorator:

```python
# TC_1418.py

import pytest
import unittest


@pytest.fixture(scope=&quot;class&quot;)
def variables_injector(request, variables):
    request.cls.variables = variables


@pytest.mark.usefixtures(&quot;variables_injector&quot;)
class Test1418(unittest.TestCase):
    def test_something(self):
        print(self.variables)
```

**Notice that the name of the class starts with `Test` so as to follow [conventions for test discovery](http://doc.pytest.org/en/latest/goodpractices.html#conventions-for-python-test-discovery).**

If you don&#39;t want to go into this travesty, I propose you rather fully embrace Pytest and make your life easier with simple test functions that you have already discovered or properly structured test classes:

```python
# TC_1418.py

class Test1418:
    def test_something(self, variables):
        print(variables)
```

